==Notes==
<sup>†</sup> As part of the process of establishment of the [[European External Action Service]] envisioned in the recently ratified [[Treaty of Lisbon]], on 1 January 2010 all former ''European Commission delegations'' were renamed into ''European Union delegations'' and till the end of the month 54 of the missions (marked with <sup>†</sup> in the list above) were transformed into [[embassy]]-type missions that employ greater powers than the regular delegations. These upgraded delegations have taken on the role previously carried out by the national embassies of the member state holding the rotating [[Presidency of the Council of the European Union]].<ref>[http://euobserver.com/9/29308 EU commission 'embassies' granted new powers], [[EUobserver]]</ref>

